                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d279">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">710.Consultation(2)/234: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Uruguay</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Montevideo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-07-09T12:00:00-03:30"
                            >July 9, 1940—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 2:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>153. A few days ago the French Minister, under instructions from his Government,
                    informed Guani<note n="44" xml:id="d279fn1">Alberto Guani, Uruguayan Minister
                        for Foreign Affairs.</note> that the French Government saw no reason why the
                    American States should discuss at Habana the question of transfer of territory
                    in the Western Hemisphere from one non-American Power to another, adding that
                    the German Government had never raised this question.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
